				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The rules were derived based on testing in a block puzzle game supporting two players. Think like Dr. Mario except on speed, as if both players were as fast as Red Virus from the Super NES version. Having two players pumping rapid fire sound effects into the system without obscuring the music too much requires a fairly robust set of heuristics.<br /><br />Sure, sound effects give information to the player. But often, most of that information lies in the loud beginning of the effect, not the quiet part at the end as it trails off. For example, the MIRV splitting sound effect in Thwaite has some single channel echo going on in it, but it's quiet at the end so that the attack of the next note covers up the echo.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

